You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

              0.0                E
    

    Example:

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

```thonpy
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. ```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

def odd_count(lst):
    """Given a list of strings, where each string consists of only digits, return a list.
    Each element i of the output should be "the number of odd elements in the

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

    """
    Given a positive integer n, return a sorted list that has the odd numbers in collatz sequence.

    The Collatz conjecture is a conjecture in mathematics that concerns a sequence defined
    as follows: start with any positive integer n. Then each term is obtained from the 
    previous term as follows: if the previous term is even, the next term is one half of 
    the previous term. If the previous term is odd, the next term is 3 times the previous
    term plus 1. The conjecture is that no matter what value of n, the sequence will always reach 1.

        2. returned list sorted in increasing order.

    For example:
    get_odd_collatz(5) returns [1, 5] # The collatz sequence for 5 is [5, 16, 8, 4, 2, 1], so the odd numbers are only 1, and 5.

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

    Your task is to determine whether the length of intersection of these two

    Example, the intersection of the intervals (1, 3), (2, 4) is (2, 3)
    which its length is 1, which not a prime number.
    If the length of the intersection is a prime number, return "YES",
    otherwise, return "NO".
    If the two intervals don't intersect, return "NO".

    intersection((-1, 1), (0, 4)) ==> "NO"
    intersection((-3, -1), (-5, 5)) ==> "YES"
    """

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

    """
    Given a grid with N rows and N columns (N >= 2) and a positive integer k, 
    each cell of the grid contains a value. Every integer in the range [1, N * N]
    inclusive appears exactly once on the cells of the grid.

    You have to find the minimum path of length k in the grid. You can start
    from any cell, and in each step you can move to any of the neighbor cells,
    in other words, you can go to cells which share an edge with you current
    cell.
    Please note that a path of length k means visiting exactly k cells (not
    necessarily distinct).
    You CANNOT go off the grid.
    A path A (of length k) is considered less than a path B (of length k) if
    after making the ordered lists of the values on the cells that A and B go
    through (let's call them lst_A and lst_B), lst_A is lexicographically less
    than lst_B, in other words, there exist an integer index i (1 <= i <= k)
    such that lst_A[i] < lst_B[i] and for any j (1 <= j < i) we have
    lst_A[j] = lst_B[j].
    It is guaranteed that the answer is unique.
    Return an ordered list of the values on the cells that the minimum path go through.

    Examples:

        Input: grid = [ [1,2,3], [4,5,6], [7,8,9]], k = 3
        Output: [1, 2, 1]

        Input: grid = [ [5,9,3], [4,1,6], [7,8,2]], k = 1
        Output: [1]
    """

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).


You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy

assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"

assert "abc"[:2] == "a"

assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]

assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

column1:
You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy

assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"

assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```

You are an expert programmer who can readily adapt to new programming languages. There is a new programming language, ThonPy, which is identical to Python 3.7 except all variables of the `list`, `tuple`, and `str` types use 1-based indexing, like in the MATLAB and R languages, where sequence indices start from 1. That is, index `n` represents the `n`-th element in a sequence, NOT the `n+1`-th as in 0-based indexing. This change only affects when the index is non-negative. When the index is negative, the behavior is the same as Python 3.7. This also affects methods of these classes such as `index` and `pop`. The built-in functions `enumerate` and `range` also use 1-based indexing: by default, the index of `enumerate` starts from 1, and so does the lower bound of `range` when not supplied (the higher bound is unchanged).

For example,
```thonpy
assert (7, 8, 9)[1] == 7
assert ["abc", "def", "ghi"][3] == "ghi"
assert "abcde"[4] == "d"
assert "abc"[:2] == "a"
assert [7, 8, 9][1:] == [7, 8, 9][1:5] == [7, 8, 9][1::1] == [7, 8, 9][:4] == [9, 8, 7][::-1] == [9, 8, 7, 6][3::-1] == [7, 8, 9]
assert list(enumerate([7, 8, 9])) == [(1, 7), (2, 8), (3, 9)]
assert list(range(2)) == [1]
assert list(range(2, 4)) == [2, 3]
assert {0: 7, 1: 8, 2: 9}[1] == 8
assert [7, 8, 9].index(8) == 2
```
